@startuml AnimalChess_MCO1

' =====================================================================
' ANIMAL CHESS - MCO1 CLASS DIAGRAM (Phase 1: movement only, no trap, console)
' No enums, no extra helper classes - just plain fields. KISS.
' =====================================================================

skinparam classAttributeIconSize 0
skinparam linetype ortho

class Animal {
  - type: String
  - rank: int
  - owner: Player
  - row: int
  - col: int
  --
  + canMoveTo(board: Board, targetRow: int, targetCol: int): boolean
  + canCapture(target: Animal): boolean
  + moveTo(targetRow: int, targetCol: int): void
}
note right of Animal
  **(1)** ONE class for all 8
  animals. "type" is just a
  String ("Elephant", "Mouse",
  etc.) and "rank" is just an
  int (8 down to 1) - set once
  in the constructor.

  No enum, no 8 subclasses.
  The few special cases (mouse
  on river, lion/tiger jump,
  elephant-vs-mouse capture)
  are just if-checks on `type`
  inside canMoveTo()/canCapture().
end note

class Space {
  - terrain: String
  - occupant: Animal
  - denOwner: Player
  --
  + isOccupied(): boolean
  + isOpponentDen(p: Player): boolean
}
note left of Space
  **(2)** terrain is just a
  String: "Land", "River", or
  "Den". Trap is left out
  entirely - not in MCO1 scope.

  denOwner stays null unless
  terrain is "Den".
end note

class Board {
  - grid: Space[9][7]
  --
  + getSpace(row: int, col: int): Space
  + isWithinBounds(row: int, col: int): boolean
  + moveAnimal(a: Animal, targetRow: int, targetCol: int): void
}
note right of Board
  **(3)** Owns the 9x7 grid.
  Game and Animal only ever
  call Board's methods, never
  touch the array directly.
end note

class Player {
  - name: String
  - color: String
  - animals: Animal[8]
  --
  + hasWon(): boolean
}
note left of Player
  **(4)** Just holds the 8
  pieces a player owns plus
  their display color.
end note

class Game {
  - board: Board
  - players: Player[2]
  - currentPlayerIndex: int
  --
  + start(): void
  + switchTurn(): void
  + checkWinner(): Player
}
note right of Game
  **(5)** The rules referee.
  Has zero System.in/System.out
  calls - that's all delegated
  to the console class below.
  This keeps the door open for
  swapping in a GUI later
  without touching this class.
end note

class AnimalChessConsole {
  - game: Game
  --
  + main(args: String[]): void
  + promptDirection(): char
  + displayBoard(): void
}
note bottom of AnimalChessConsole
  **(6)** The ONLY class that
  reads L/R/U/D and prints the
  board. Entry point of the
  program (has main()).
end note

' ===================== RELATIONSHIPS =====================

AnimalChessConsole "1" *-- "1" Game : drives >
Game "1" *-- "1" Board : manages >
Game "1" *-- "2" Player : has >
Board "1" *-- "63" Space : contains >
Player "1" *-- "8" Animal : owns >
Space "1" o-- "0..1" Animal : occupant >
Space "0..1" -- "0..1" Player : denOwner

note as Walkthrough
  **(7) Read order:** AnimalChessConsole (entry point, has main())
  -> Game (turn loop + win check) -> Board (the 9x7 grid) ->
  Space (one cell - terrain/occupant) -> Animal (the piece) ->
  back up to Player (who owns it).

  **(8) Why no enums:** "type" and "terrain" are just Strings,
  "rank" is just an int. Simplest possible representation -
  swap to enums later in MCO2 if it's actually causing bugs.

  **(9) Still NOT here on purpose:** Trap rules, GUI classes,
  Controller/View split, AI opponent. All out of MCO1 scope.
end note

@enduml
